# Cases Reference Content

The foundation of Greek grammar: understanding cases through three essential questions.

## Purpose

Teach the case system conceptually before showing pronoun forms. Cases explain WHY word endings change.

## Key Insight

In English, word order shows meaning ("The dog bit the man" vs "The man bit the dog").
In Greek, word ENDINGS show meaning, so word order is flexible. These endings are called cases.

---

## The Four Questions (Hero Element)

<paradigm name="quick-rules" purpose="Core case identification">
<principle>Ask these questions to know which case to use.</principle>
<example-noun>Γιάννης (Giannis) - showing how the name changes form</example-noun>

| Question           | Answer       | Greek Example      | Translation       |
|--------------------|--------------|--------------------|--------------------|
| WHO does it?       | Nominative   | ο Γιάννης τρέχει   | Giannis runs       |
| WHOM/WHAT do I [verb]? | Accusative | βλέπω τον Γιάννη  | I see Giannis      |
| WHOSE is it?       | Genitive     | το σπίτι του Γιάννη | Giannis's house   |

<guidance>
Focus on Nominative and Accusative first. They cover most of what you'll encounter.
Genitive comes up with possession and some prepositions.
</guidance>
</paradigm>

